<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="298" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1381,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1381,1406]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(after 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams" box="[388,682,1381,1406]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" refString="Williams, D. J. &amp; Watson, G. W. (1988) The scale insects of the tropical South Pacific Region. Pt. 1. The armoured scales (Diaspididae). CAB International, Wallingford, 290 pp." type="book" year="1988">
Williams &amp; Watson, 
<number box="[621,682,1382,1406]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="1988.0">1988</number>
</bibRefCitation>
): Adult female on slide (
<figureCitation box="[956,1021,1381,1406]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[203,1398,203,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[203,1403,203,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Fiorinia phantasma (Cockerell &amp; Robinson); original illustration of the holotype of F. coronata from Williams &amp; Watson (1988), with dorsal features shown on the left side and ventral characteristics on the right. A = body of adult female; B = detail of pygidium; C = detail of anterior spiracle; D = Dorsum of second-instar female pygidium, E = detail of antennae and inter-antennal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244851/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Fig. 
<number box="[1008,1021,1382,1406]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A) about 0.65 mm long, broadly subrectangular, widest at about second abdominal segment, then narrowing abruptly to a triangular pygidium; body membranous except for lightly sclerotized pygidium; interantennal process (
<figureCitation box="[1001,1066,1453,1478]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[203,1398,203,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[203,1403,203,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Fiorinia phantasma (Cockerell &amp; Robinson); original illustration of the holotype of F. coronata from Williams &amp; Watson (1988), with dorsal features shown on the left side and ventral characteristics on the right. A = body of adult female; B = detail of pygidium; C = detail of anterior spiracle; D = Dorsum of second-instar female pygidium, E = detail of antennae and inter-antennal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244851/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Fig. 
<number box="[1053,1066,1454,1478]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
E) rounded, bearing short to long spicules, sometimes reduced in size and with only 
<number box="[718,732,1490,1514]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="1.0">1</number>
or 
<number box="[769,783,1490,1514]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="2.0">2</number>
spicules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1381,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Pygidium (
<figureCitation box="[323,388,1525,1550]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[203,1398,203,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[203,1403,203,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Fiorinia phantasma (Cockerell &amp; Robinson); original illustration of the holotype of F. coronata from Williams &amp; Watson (1988), with dorsal features shown on the left side and ventral characteristics on the right. A = body of adult female; B = detail of pygidium; C = detail of anterior spiracle; D = Dorsum of second-instar female pygidium, E = detail of antennae and inter-antennal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244851/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Fig. 
<number box="[375,388,1526,1550]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B) with notch at apex formed by parallel median lobes separated by about the width of 
<number box="[1360,1374,1526,1550]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="1.0">1</number>
lobe; median lobes yoked by internal sclerosis, each lobe with pointed apex and 
<number box="[989,1003,1562,1586]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="1.0">1</number>
or 
<number box="[1041,1055,1562,1586]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="2.0">2</number>
distal notches. Second lobes each bilobed, with inner lobule narrower than median lobe, with rounded apex approximately level with tip of median lobe; outer lobule smaller and shorter than inner lobule. Gland spines apparently absent. Long setae present between median and second lobes, and lateral to second lobes. Marginal ducts narrow, each about 
<date box="[1284,1313,1669,1694]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
<number box="[1284,1298,1669,1694]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="6.0">6</number>
x
</date>
as long as wide, numbering 
<number box="[348,362,1706,1730]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="4.0">4</number>
on each side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1381,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Ventral surface with perivulvar pores present in 
<number box="[747,761,1741,1766]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="5.0">5</number>
elongate groups. Microducts present around submargins of pygidium, forward to about abdominal segment III; others present in median areas of free abdominal segments, and lateral to labium. Duct tubercles present in single, interrupted marginal row between mesothorax to abdominal segment II. Antennae set close together on margin of head, each bearing 
<number box="[979,993,1850,1874]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="1.0">1</number>
long seta (
<figureCitation box="[1119,1186,1849,1874]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[203,1398,203,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[203,1403,203,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Fiorinia phantasma (Cockerell &amp; Robinson); original illustration of the holotype of F. coronata from Williams &amp; Watson (1988), with dorsal features shown on the left side and ventral characteristics on the right. A = body of adult female; B = detail of pygidium; C = detail of anterior spiracle; D = Dorsum of second-instar female pygidium, E = detail of antennae and inter-antennal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244851/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Fig. 
<number box="[1172,1186,1850,1874]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
E). Antennal spiracles each associated with 
<number box="[388,402,1886,1910]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="2.0">2</number>
disc pores, each pore containing 
<number box="[776,790,1886,1910]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="3.0">3</number>
loculi (
<figureCitation box="[876,943,1885,1910]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[203,1398,203,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[203,1403,203,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Fiorinia phantasma (Cockerell &amp; Robinson); original illustration of the holotype of F. coronata from Williams &amp; Watson (1988), with dorsal features shown on the left side and ventral characteristics on the right. A = body of adult female; B = detail of pygidium; C = detail of anterior spiracle; D = Dorsum of second-instar female pygidium, E = detail of antennae and inter-antennal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244851/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Fig. 
<number box="[929,943,1886,1910]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1381,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Second-instar exuviae moderately sclerotized, with a small median patch of thinner cuticle near the anterior margin located approximately over interantennal process of adult female. Pygidial margin with 
<number box="[1309,1323,1957,1982]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="5.0">5</number>
marginal macroducts (
<figureCitation box="[295,361,1993,2018]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[203,1398,203,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[203,1403,203,1882]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Fiorinia phantasma (Cockerell &amp; Robinson); original illustration of the holotype of F. coronata from Williams &amp; Watson (1988), with dorsal features shown on the left side and ventral characteristics on the right. A = body of adult female; B = detail of pygidium; C = detail of anterior spiracle; D = Dorsum of second-instar female pygidium, E = detail of antennae and inter-antennal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244851/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
Fig. 
<number box="[348,361,1994,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
D), each duct about 
<date box="[588,616,1994,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296">
<number box="[588,602,1994,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="296" value="2.0">2</number>
x
</date>
longer than wide.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244851/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="297" targetBox="[203,1398,203,1866]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1915,2028]" pageId="6" pageNumber="297">
